venue.name: Wistaria Tea House (紫藤廬 Wistaria Tea House)

tip.text: If you’re looking to expand your wardrobe, and branded not being a must, a visit here may appeal. Mostly cheap offerings, but quality is very relative to price! ~10–15m walk from Raohe St Night Mkt.

venue.name: 五分埔時尚購物通 Wufenpu Clothes Market

tip.text: Located at Taipei Fish Market, this establishment hosts an array of Japanese-themed foods, consisting of both cooked and uncooked. Oh, the sushi bar is AMAZING — a must-try! • *Cash only* • Go early!
Local hot pot restaurant, buffet style. Food is very fresh; wide variety of items! Excellent drinks & dessert bar (for that “extra stomach” that some of us have!) 1h30m sessions; booking recommended!
Pork buns! (Get the half-lean, half-fat version: best balance of tasty & good amounts of meat) • Soups! (Go for the pork-with-corn) • Good time to go is between meal times → small queues. Best snack!
An original “Made in Ximending” food stop: a stand-up noodle shop, serving thin noodles (‘misua’ or ‘mee sua’) in a thick broth with condiments. Add chilli/garlic/vinegar to your preference. Just 😋!
A mall, commercial offices, and — most importantly, the observatory at the very top of the tower. A must-visit if you’ve never been!

formattedAddress: 信義區信義路五段7號 (松智路)

tip.text: A must-visit location if you’ve never been. Entry fee via ticket purchase inside the mall. Make sure to go when it’s a clear day (or night!) — the view of Taipei, like other Asian cities, is amazing!

The Taiwanese version of JR’s Shinkansen in Japan. Emulates the experience very well at all levels (great ride, friendly service, fast!) Travel btwn Taipei, Taichung & Kaohsiung (~100 min end-to-end).

contact.facebookName: 台灣高鐵台北站 THSR Taipei Station

tip.text: Famous for their face-sized, deep-fried chicken cutlets. Can be had with or without chilli. Ideally share with others (quite a lot!) • While there are branches, this is the “home” store (sentimental).

formattedAddress: 文林路113號 (士林夜市50號攤)

tip.text: Not the famous Shilin “Night” Market, but a real market located right next to it in the area. A more down-to-earth collection of stores, as well as entertainment, for all ages. • Food court below.
If you’re sick of the night market’s craziness, and want some proper food (proper meal), it can be found here — below the real Shilin Market. Besides food, the juice store next to the stairs is 👌🏼!

The one-and-only item: brown sugar bubble tea (but no tea inside) • Actually, it’s a drink with rich milk + brown sugar + perfectly-cooked black pearls (“bubble”). My first-stop shop on Taipei visits!

venue.name: 陳三鼎黑糖青蛙鮮奶創始店

tip.text: Serves alright barista-type coffee, and is situated right next to the pier for ferries to Cijin (a small island around 10 mins ride each way). Probably worth getting take-away from if you’re queuing.

formattedAddress: 濱海二路5號 (鼓山渡輪站)

tip.text: Seemingly the main night market in Kaohsiung, with all its hustle-and-bustle. You can practically find all kinds of food and drinks here, whether it’s new or old. One visit is certainly not enough! 🤔
Prepared to be time-warped back to the 60s/70s! A very unique atmosphere where you can enjoy various local dishes (meals) and other delights. Tried the pork chop, with veges, rice and soup. Just yum!
This is the one everyone talks about, and rightly so for the vast amounts (and variations) of food/drinks/retail lining the streets and laneways. Big crowds; more focused on quantity, not quality.

tip.text: A smaller night market offering food/drinks and a bit of retail in between. If you hate big crowds, this may be one to visit! 😉

If you’re hoping to order tea with their famous pineapple cakes, think again! Customers are seated & presented with a single portion (sample) of cake with tea (refillable). Purchase expected, I think.
Best local breakfast joint in Taipei! Highly recommended: youtiao (big, deep-fried dough sticks — best I’ve ever had!) and soya bean drink (can be had hot/cold, with/out sugar) • Expect to queue!

formattedAddress: 忠孝東路一段108號2F (紹興南街)

venue.name: Fu Hang Dou Jiang (阜杭豆漿)

tip.text: One of the quieter, lesser-renowned night markets in Taipei, yet it still offers an abundance of local quite-bites and delights. Check out the neighbouring food/drinks stores too while you’re there!
Best English Breakfast I’ve ever had! The scrambled eggs were fluffy and fragrant; bacon had minimal fat and cooked to perfection; and there was even black pudding! ē French Toast was also awesome! 😄
